{{Houʻeiki|fakanofo= Tuʻi Tonga Fefine |ʻaho fakanofo= ~1600 |ʻaho fakamālōlō= |ki muʻa=(ʻuluaki ia) |hoko= [[ʻEkutongapipiki]] |}}
{{Kāinga ofi|faʻahinga=fale ʻalo |maama= fefine |tamai= [[ʻUluakimata I]] |faʻē= [[Mataukipā]] |ʻaho fanauʻi= ~1600 |ʻaho pekia= |taʻokete-tokoua= {{tokoua|||||||||}} |taʻokete-lau= {{tokoua|||||||||}} |tehina-tokoua= {{tokoua|[[Fatafehi]]||||||||}} |ʻohoana1=[[Tapuʻosi (TL)|Tapuʻosi]] |fānau1= {{tokoua|[[Fonomanu]]|[[Fonokimoana]]|||||||}} |}}*I.C. Campbell, Island kingdom, Canterbury university press, 1992, 2001 *D.V. Burley; Sacred child and sacred place; Polynesian paradox, USP 2005; ISBN 982-02-0371-6 Ko hono huafa ko '''Sinaitakala''' pē. Naʻa ne telio ʻi he [[ʻotu langi|langi Leka]]. Naʻe fuʻu māʻolunga hono ʻuhinga, naʻe ʻikai ha tokotaha ʻi Tonga ʻe lava taʻane mo Sinaitakala, ko e Tuʻi Tonga Fefine ʻuluaki. Monū, naʻe ʻi ai ha ʻeiki mei Fisi, ko e Tui Lakeba, ko Tapuʻosi ia. Ko hono huafa fakanofo ʻoku ʻi tuʻa ʻo e founga fakatonga.
Ko ia, naʻe kamata ʻa e hako ʻo e [[:category:Tamahā|Tamahā]] (ʻofefine taʻoketelele) mo e [[:category:Haʻa Falefisi|Fale Fisi]], ko ē: [[:category:Tuʻilakepa|Tuʻilakepa]], [[:category:Tuʻihaʻateiho|Tuʻihaʻateiho]] mo e ngaahi haʻa kehe.
Ko Sinaitakalaʻilangileka ko hono hoa ko Tapuʻosi (ko e tangata mei Fisi) ko hona ʻapi ʻafioʻanga ʻi [[Muʻa]] naʻe tuʻu ia he feituʻu naʻe ʻiloa ko [[Talasiu]], pea oku ʻi ai ai pe mo hona [[ʻotu langi|langi]] fakafāmili, ʻa ia ko "Nakulukilangi".
{{English|more}}

In another version of the story the name Lātūtoevave is given as Lātūteovave, and he is also the middle brother, that is older than Melinoʻatonga and Lotauai.

Takalaua was murdered too, while having a meal on the island [[Mataʻaho (Tongatapu)|Mataʻaho]] (in the lagoon). It was by two men from [[ʻUvea]] named Tamasia and Malofafa.
{{Foki||Takalaua}}

Kauʻulufonua and his brothers chased the murderers of their father, Tamasia and Molofaha. They fought their allies on all islands from Tongatapu to ʻUvea, until they finally captured them.

His oldest son, Fotofili was sent away to become governor on Niuafoʻou. It seems however, that the old man who told the story, was confused. The Fotofili normally connected with this lived generations later.
{{Foki||Kauʻulufonua (fekai)}}

Vakafuhu lived on Sāmoa, driven out as he was by the Tuʻi Haʻatakalaua.

Possibly the Vakafuhu who is the father of the fishgod Tuʻitofua is a different person.
{{Foki||Vakafuhu}}

There are 33 traditional noble titles in the current nation of Tonga. They all are estate holders. 20 titles were established by Siaosi Tupou I with the constitution of 1875. In 1880 he added 10 more. Tupou II created the titles Lasike in 1894 and Veikune in 1903. Sālote Tupou III made in 1921 the title of Tupoutoʻa. In the beginning it was forbidden for a noble to have more than one title. Later this was made possible.
Some of the great chiefs who missed out on a noble's title (in 1910) were among others: [[ʻAlipate Mafileʻo]] of [[Kolomotuʻa]], [[SA Sipu]] of [[Kolomotuʻa]], [[Iki Tupou Fulivai|Iki Lolohea]] of [[:category:Haʻapai|Haʻapai]] (but later inherited the [[:category:Fulivai|Fulivai]]), [[Tēvita Tapueluelu]] of [[:category:Vavaʻu|Vavaʻu]], [[SF Tafolo]], [[Tēvita Ula Afuhaʻamango]] of [[:category:Vavaʻu|Vavaʻu]], [[Siosiua Niutupuʻivaha Kaho‎‎]] (but later inherited the [[:category:Tuʻivakanō|Tuʻivakanō]]).
These unacknowledged chiefs were still lords in the traditional sense. However their influence slowly decreased with each passing generation. Queen Sālote acknowledged this in some of her public speeches by paying respect to the chiefs then a separate respect to the Nobles of the Crown as: «Tapu mo Houʻeiki pea Tapu ki he Kau Nopele ʻa e Fonua». {{Foki|f|Nōpele}}

As the sister of the Tuʻi Tonga, Sinaitakala was too highly ranked to marry any Tongan, she formed a class on herself, she was the first [[:category:Tuʻi Tonga Fefine|Tuʻi Tonga Fefine]]. Luckily she fell in love with a chief from Fiji, Tapuʻosi, the Tui Lakeba, who was outside the Tongan ranking system.
With her started the [[:category:Tamahā|Tamahā]] (her children, especially her oldest daughter) and the [[:category:Haʻa Falefisi|Fale Fisi]] (chiefs perhaps higher than the Tuʻi Tonga, but as outsiders not a treat to him).
[[Tokiukamea]] mentions the name ''Chenitacala'' (English pronunciation, with the 's' still a 'j' in that time) as a goddess, the soul of a once great chiefess. {{Foki||Sinaitakalaʻilangileka}}

Tamahā is a word from Sāmoan origin: ''tama sā'', meaning holy child. She was the oldest daughter of a [[:category:Tuʻi Tonga Fefine|Tuʻi Tonga Fefine]]. Most of them stayed at the small but glorious island of [[Tungua]] in Haʻapai, so that their high rank did not interfere with matters of state, conducted by the lords on Tongatapu. The institution was established in the beginning of the 17th century, around the time that the Tongan ranking system developed into what it is nowadays.
Tradition (see: E.W. Gifford, Tongan society, 1929) names 6 Tamahā, starting with [[Fonokimoana]], an ending with [[ʻAmelia Fakahikuʻoʻuiha]], when the line of the [[:category:Tuʻi Tonga|Tuʻi Tonga]] also collapsed. On the other hand queen [[Sālote Tupou III]] (see: E. Bott, Tongan society at the time of Captain Cook's visits, 1982) only recognised 3 Tamahā, crossing off those who were not the oldest child of a Tuʻi Tonga Fefine.
A Tamahā was officially installed. Unlike their mothers, there was only one Tamahā at any given time, if any, and a potential contestant had to wait until the death of her predecessor before she could get the title. *D.V. Burley; Sacred child and sacred place; Polynesian paradox, USP 2005; ISBN 982-02-0371-6 {{Foki|f|Tamahā}}

Moʻungaʻotonga married a virgin from Sāmoa, a privilige until then only allowed to the [[:Category:Tuʻi Tonga|Tuʻi Tonga]], as that act increased his rank. Apparently so highly risen had the Tuʻi Takalaua by now that he could come away with it and had even with his son [[Ngata]] another dynasty started.
Moʻungaʻotonga's first son would succeed him as Tuʻi Haʻatakalaua. His second, Niukapu, was sent out as governor of Haʻapai. The third, Nuku, became governor of the Hahake district, large and rich. The fourth and youngest, Ngata had to do it with Hihifo, always been the smallest and poorest district.
Who could have guessed that from him the mightiest line of kings would come forth? And nowadays the descendants of Nuku and Niukapu are under those of Ngata, and they belong to the [[:Category:Haʻa Lātūhifo|Lātūhifo clan]] (low Lātū). {{Foki||Moʻungaʻotonga}}

The offspring of the three younger brothers, Niukapu, Nuku and Ngata are also called the '''ʻUlutolu''' (triple head). During the time of Ngata, even his son and grandson, they were not yet known as Tuʻi Kanokupolu. Ngata's title was the '''Tuʻi Haʻamoʻunga'''.
There were other sons of Ngata, and they, and their sons, were the first contributants to his dynasty, their descendants are known as the old Ngata clan: [[:category:Haʻa Ngata Motuʻa|Haʻa Ngata Motuʻa]].
[[Vakalepuʻahio]] (short ʻAhio) was Ngata's oldest son, but he refused to accept the Tuʻi Kanokupolu title on his father's death, leaving it to his younger stepbrother [[Atamataʻila]] (short Ata). Because he did not like, or felt himself too good, to be a servant to the real king (his uncle [[Fotofili]]). At that time the Tuʻi Kanokupolu was still barely any more than that compared to the Tuʻi Haʻatakalaua. Still nowadays the [[:category:ʻAhio|ʻAhio]] clan, being the head of the Haʻa Ngata Motuʻa, has despite that position, no traditional duties. {{Foki||Ngata}}

This was the first time that a daughter of the Tuʻi Haʻatakalaua married with a Tuʻi Tonga. This would from now on strengthen the links between the two families. Kalo-afu-tonga was the first [[māʻitaki]]. The word is clearly related to the Sāmoan ''tama'itaʻi'' (lady).

Campbell's spelling her name as Kaluafotonga must be a mistake.
{{Foki||Kaloafūtonga}}

