Fēfē ko e tuʻunga ʻo [[Sisifā]] ʻi heni ?

{{Houʻeiki|fakanofo= Maʻafu |ʻaho fakanofo= ~1700 |ʻaho fakamālōlō= |ki muʻa= (ʻuluaki ia) |hoko= [[Mailelaumotomoto]] |}}
{{Kāinga ofi|faʻahinga=houʻeiki |maama= tangata |tamai=[[Mataeletuʻapiko]] |faʻē=Papa |ʻaho fanauʻi= ~1700 |ʻaho pekia= |taʻokete-tokoua= {{tokoua|[[Mataelehaʻamea]]|[[Vuna Tuʻiʻoetau]]|[[Afualo]]|[[Vaivai]]|||||}} |taʻokete-lau= {{tokoua|&nbsp;|&nbsp;|&nbsp;|&nbsp;|||||}} |tehina-tokoua= {{tokoua|||||||||}} |ʻohoana1=Sauliloa |fānau1= {{tokoua|[[Mailelaumotomoto]]||||||||}} |}}*I.C. Campbell, Island kingdom, Canterbury university press, 1992, 2001
Ko ia foki mo hono tokoua, naʻa nau kamata ha haʻa foʻou, ko [[:category:Haʻa Havea lahi|Haʻa Havea lahi]], pea ko e kāinga ʻo [[:category:Maʻafu|Maʻafu]] ko hono ʻulu ia.

After the murder on [[Tukuʻaho]] on 21 April 1799, whole [[:Category:Tongatapu & takatakai|Tongatapu]] fell into disarray. All the chiefs wanted to have the prestigeous title of [[:category:Tuʻi Kanokupolu|Tuʻi Kanokupolu]] but none was strong enough to enforce his wish upon the others. In fact the main instignator of the murder, [[Fīnau ʻUlukālala II ʻi Feletoa (Fangupō)]] showed his disdain by putting a pig on the throne. Many battles followed. It was not until the death of [[Mulikihaʻamea]] on 29 May 1799 that the [[:category:Haʻa Havea lahi|Haʻa Havea lahi]] enforced their candidate: Maʻafuʻolimuloa, the younger son of [[Tangataʻilavalu]], who would have to yield in due time the [[:category:Maʻafu|Maʻafu]] title to his elder brother. An outsider, since his family had split off from the main line several generations ago, as such he was not considered as belonging to the 'family'.
Anyway, at the following [[ʻinasi]] he was installed as Tuʻi Kanokupolu, but it is not known exactly when, as the yearly ʻinasi ceremonies were during July or October. It may even have been as late as the next year, April 1800. Whatever the date, Maʻafuʻolimuloa was murdered the night of his installation. But whether this was done by ʻUlukālala again or by members of the [[:Category:Haʻa Ngata Tupu|Haʻa Ngata tupu]], a senior clan of the Tuʻi Kanokupolu line, is not clear.
It would take about 10 years before finally the next Tuʻi Kanokupolu was selected, and then still only accepted by merely a few chiefs. {{Foki||Maʻafuʻolimuloa}}

