*http://www.familysearch.org/Eng/search/AF/family_group_record.asp?familyid=9014685&frompage=99 ʻOku nau tala naʻa ne faʻeleʻi ʻi 1797. ʻOku faingataʻa mo ha foha mei he taʻu tatau.

'''Fata-na-lua''', an old form for ''double platform'', possibly the same as Fātungaloa, is a traditional constellation, said to consist of two lines of four stars, named Fata-ʻolalo (lower platform) and Fata-ʻolunga (upper platform). It is also said to be "close" to both Orion and Scorpius (which in reality are almost diametrically opposite each other in the sky). It might refer to Coma Berenices, a faint and inconspicious constellation.

It was used as a starpath to Fiji by captain Tēvita Fifita when his ship, the Tuaikaepau, was wrecked on Minerva reef in 1962.
{{Foki||Fatanalua}}

'''Fetuʻu ʻaho''' (= day star) is a traditional Tongan star appearing around dawn, it is the morning star. Said in Tonga: it rises before the rising of the sun. Any star of planet which satisfies this condition, although normally reserved for the planet Venus only. Equal to the word ''fetū ao'' in Sāmoan.

As evening star Venus is known as [[Tapukitea]].
{{Foki||Fetuʻuʻaho}}

The '''Humu''' (Coalsack) is the name of a dark patch in the milkyway, close the constellation of Crux (southern cross). It is so named, because it has the shape of a triggerfish, [[humu (ika)|humu]].
In the myth of the both Maʻafu, humu was a fresh water fish, caught by the two boys, and later together with a [[toloa (manupuna)|toloa]] and the twin themselves placed into the sky.
Even when not in the sky Humu and Toloa are still good friends as in the following trite: Humu and Toloa plant their plantain plant plant then overgrown with bush. A Fiji dog runs along being welcomed with a shot missed in the leg but hit in the liver It then let out its loud cry. {{Foki||Humu (langi)}}

'''Toloa''' is a constellation in the sky, also known by its name copied from English: the Southern cross (Crux). But in the Tongan mind the stars of the cross rather outline a duck flying over to the south.
In the myth of the both Maʻafu, the duck was a wild bird, but was caught by the twins, and later together with Humu and them placed in the sky. In another myth the western wing of Toloa is wounded because [[Ongo tangata|Two men]] threw stones at it. The star on that spot is fainter than the others.
When not in the sky, Toloa and [[Humu (langi)|Humu]] are still two good friends. {{Foki||Toloa (pupunga)}}

{{Houʻeiki|fakanofo= Tuʻihaʻangana |ʻaho fakanofo= ~1800 |ʻaho fakamālōlō= |ki muʻa= [[Fifitapuku]] |hoko= [[Lataimaumi Havea]] |}}
{{Kāinga ofi |faʻahinga= houʻeiki |maama= tangata |tamai= [[Fifitapuku]] |faʻē= [[Fatafehi ʻo Lapaha]] |ʻaho fanauʻi= ~1780 |ʻaho pekia= |taʻokete-tokoua= {{tokoua|||||||||}} |taʻokete-lau= {{tokoua|||||||||}} |tehina-tokoua= {{tokoua|||||||||}} |ʻohoana1= Lolohea Kulukulutea aka Uini |fānau1= {{tokoua|ʻAlai-ʻi-Lupe Lahi|Lesieli Kilinganoa|Tupou Moheofo|Tuʻifua ʻo Vavaʻulahi|Sione Fili moe Hakau Tofua|Sione Fuapau|Tolutau|Kuila|}} |ʻohoana2= [[Hulitā Tuʻifua Fuaʻotonga]] |fānau2= {{tokoua|[[Fifita Vavaʻu]]||||||||}} |ʻohoana3= [[Tāufa Hoamofaleono]] |fānau3= {{tokoua|[[Fifita Holeva]]||||||||}} |ʻohoana4= [[Puleʻilangitē Lāvaka]] |fānau4= {{tokoua|[[Lataimaumi Havea]]|Fehoko Manavahetau|Tae Tunaʻula||||||}} |}}Pea ʻoku toe ha ngaahi ʻohoana/sinifu mo e fānau, ʻa ia: *Mele, hako: Hulu Tungua *Folau, hako: Fotu ʻi Hala Tata, Siotame Havea (Fatai FOTOFILI) *taʻeʻiloa, hako: Moa ʻEueiki
Naʻe pehē ʻe [[Tokiukamea]], ko Liufau, ko e ʻeiki ʻo [[Haʻano]], ko ha puletau ʻe taha ia ʻo [[Fīnau ʻUlukālala II ʻi Feletoa (Fangupō)]] lolotonga heʻene tau ki [[:Category:Vavaʻu|Vavaʻu]] ʻi 1808. Naʻe talatalaakiʻia ia ʻi heʻene lavaki, kā naʻe ʻikai ʻi ai ha fakamoʻoni. Naʻa ne toe ki he kau muimui ʻo Fīnau.
