The '''pōpao''' is the Tongan word for outrigger canoe, a hollowed out tree trunk carrying one or a few fishermen onto the quiet lagoon (not on the large).
Main parts: *''katea'', the larger hull *''kiato'', the cross beams connecting the both hulls *''hama'' (or ''ama''), the smaller hull or outrigger *''tauama'', the sticks and ropes connecting the outrigger to the crossbeams. The '''U''' shape is characteristic for Tonga.
When the 2 hulls are more or less equal in size (as for the [[kalia]]), they are called ''fakatoukatea''. {{foki||Pōpao}}

